The 3 volunteer demands included in this research were emotional demands (measured with 6 items: eg, “I have to deal with people who have unrealistic expectations”
52
), conflict with paid staff was measured with 3 items that were developed on the basis of previous qualitative data on volunteers (eg, “I find it difficult to communicate with paid staff”
53
), and work–home conflict (4 items: eg “The demands of volunteer work interfere with my family/home/social life”
54
). The response options for all the demands subscales were ranging from 1 (strongly disagree) to 5 (strongly agree), with high scores indicating higher volunteer demands.

The 4 volunteer resources included in the study were supervisor/coordinator support (4 items: eg, “My supervisor/coordinator is concerned about my welfare”
55
), volunteer training (5 items: eg, “The workshops and seminars, eg, monthly support groups; available to me through this organization help improve my palliative caring skills”
56
), volunteer organizational support (5 items: eg, “The organization provides adequate reimbursement for my out-of-pocket expenses”
40
), and family support (4 items; eg, “My friends/family care about how I feel about my volunteer work”
57
). The same response options as for the demands subscales were used.

The Burnout dimensions were measured using the Maslach Burnout Inventory–General Survey (MBI-GS
58
). Exhaustion was measured with the respective 5-item scale with examples like “I feel emotionally drained from my (volunteer) work”; while Cynicism was measured with 4 items such as “I doubt the significance of my (volunteer) work.” Volunteers rated their answers in a scale ranging from 0 = never to 6 = everyday.
